<subSubSection id="627925004BA9EE1C48F98E555C5A087F" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="4D61A052235E1609079898700D970460" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E179D72D26D4CD03521C32031F9FDAAF" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Small-sized holothurian (up to 49 mm), 20 peltate tentacles, no distinct collar; anal papillae present. Podia as conical papillae dorsally and tube feet ventrally. Body wall thin, leathery. Single Polian vesicle, free stone canal. Ossicles as tables, buttons, pseudo-buttons and supporting rods, tube feet with perforated plates. Table discs spinose to smooth with 6-13 marginal holes; spire of moderate height, one cross-beam, terminating in a crown with 14-20 teeth, such crown with a high shape diversity. Pseudo-buttons (25-50 
<normalizedToken id="141DFF724C793E3604E21D634F207CFB" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
long) mostly irregular, often twisted and/or knobbed, with two to five holes. Dorsal papillae and tube feet with curved supporting rods (180-240 
<normalizedToken id="8EF09C99E5AC2C482BF6ED8DEC44917A" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
), ends and central part are widened and perforated, the edge of the widened part slightly spinose. Tentacles with slightly curved rods, spiny ends, without perforations (300-600 
<normalizedToken id="2B21A9A2E467C37887B0D3C288F79F28" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="DE2384251278BCC44286B8B57A8D5FDE" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="description">
<paragraph id="F49DD8F7C96FEC0446199C8D3E4ECC43" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Holotype description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C4607AB1DF726BE0C2ED86385307824F" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Specimen preserved in alcohol with brownish body wall, the papillae, and ventral tube feet are white; 20 short beige tentacles. Ventral and dorsal body wall with minute white dots due to the presence of ossicle clusters. Anus surrounded by anal papillae. Calcareous ring stout (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="B56F44FF6646ABC203A0DAAD3684CFA3" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Holothuria (Lessonothuria) coronata sp. nov. Holotype, ICML-UNAM 18432. Calcareous ring. Single ventral and dorsal radials (R) and adjoining interradial plates (Ir)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.79375.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671978" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">4</figureCitation>
), interradial pieces with a median anterior projection; radial pieces with a median anterior notch and much wider than the interradial pieces; dorsal radial pieces are wider and stouter than the ventral ones. Polian vesicle 10 mm long. Free stone canal, 2 mm long. Single madreporite. Longitudinal muscles divided, 8-10 mm wide. Tentacular ampullae 5 mm long. Cuvierian organs present.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2B94006186BAF43D524C6BA3F99A85F4" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis id="2BD11876D5286C736E2CD9A30CBE201A" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis id="B37B28AC81D31907D18B499B6F37A6C3" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ossicles</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Dorsal papillae with three types of tables, supporting rods, and a reduced terminal plate. The first type of table possesses circular disc (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="AED3E6EF7DB776AC8FDD9543109CAFA5" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Holothuria (Lessonothuria) coronata sp. nov. Holotype, ICML-UNAM 18432. Ossicles of dorsal papillae (A-F) A tables B table with irregular disc C table with reduced disc D ' rare table' of the dorsal E supporting rod and table F supporting rods. Ossicles of dorsal body wall (G-I) G tables H pseudo-buttons I buttons. Ossicles of tentacles J rods." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.79375.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671976" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">2A</figureCitation>
), sometimes irregular (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="B3128D346C9AADD3EE310AB7B897A12B" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Holothuria (Lessonothuria) coronata sp. nov. Holotype, ICML-UNAM 18432. Ossicles of dorsal papillae (A-F) A tables B table with irregular disc C table with reduced disc D ' rare table' of the dorsal E supporting rod and table F supporting rods. Ossicles of dorsal body wall (G-I) G tables H pseudo-buttons I buttons. Ossicles of tentacles J rods." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.79375.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671976" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">2B</figureCitation>
), diameter of 50-70 
<normalizedToken id="AF5C3C46FFDB2E6EE4C523188A320876" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
, the rim is either smooth or spinous and turned up; four big central holes and 6-13 peripheral holes, sometimes a second series of smaller peripheral holes is present. Spire is low to medium and consists of four pillars, spiny crown with a central hole; single cross-beam. The second type of table (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="5E2963FFC56EE0123A4625169521DBEF" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Holothuria (Lessonothuria) coronata sp. nov. Holotype, ICML-UNAM 18432. Ossicles of dorsal papillae (A-F) A tables B table with irregular disc C table with reduced disc D ' rare table' of the dorsal E supporting rod and table F supporting rods. Ossicles of dorsal body wall (G-I) G tables H pseudo-buttons I buttons. Ossicles of tentacles J rods." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.79375.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671976" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">2C</figureCitation>
) has a reduced disc with irregular rim, four central holes, and usually lacking peripheral holes, but some tables bear up to three peripheral holes. Spire is medium size (35-45 
<normalizedToken id="B678E3AE74CB9D70B44A0F624F1C5DC8" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
) and consists of four pillars, spiny crown with a central hole; single cross-beam. The third type of table (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="84C3792FD258BB31CF01650CA39A8A8B" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Holothuria (Lessonothuria) coronata sp. nov. Holotype, ICML-UNAM 18432. Ossicles of dorsal papillae (A-F) A tables B table with irregular disc C table with reduced disc D ' rare table' of the dorsal E supporting rod and table F supporting rods. Ossicles of dorsal body wall (G-I) G tables H pseudo-buttons I buttons. Ossicles of tentacles J rods." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.79375.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671976" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">2D</figureCitation>
) has reduced disc and smooth rim, four big central holes. Zero to seven peripheral holes, spire of four pillars; spiny crown. Curved supporting rods (140-240 
<normalizedToken id="D1B98D2B0F9170310E2CA71704A25AA3" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
) (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="2541DFBB59F3510DA712959185849F84" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Holothuria (Lessonothuria) coronata sp. nov. Holotype, ICML-UNAM 18432. Ossicles of dorsal papillae (A-F) A tables B table with irregular disc C table with reduced disc D ' rare table' of the dorsal E supporting rod and table F supporting rods. Ossicles of dorsal body wall (G-I) G tables H pseudo-buttons I buttons. Ossicles of tentacles J rods." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.79375.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671976" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">2E, F</figureCitation>
), the ends and the central part are widened and perforated; spiny edge. Reduced terminal plate, 50-60 
<normalizedToken id="4266F74B03B6FABCAEC6D506B4AD3A66" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
wide. Anal papillae with three types of tables and supporting rods, these four types of ossicles are identical to those present in the dorsal papillae. Dorsal body wall with tables, buttons, and pseudo-buttons. Tables with circular disc (45-60 
<normalizedToken id="D6D6B781AC2C9834BDFB559E0B1857E3" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
wide) (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="6CB00E2E9B942EB458F1564DF5BBF861" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Holothuria (Lessonothuria) coronata sp. nov. Holotype, ICML-UNAM 18432. Ossicles of dorsal papillae (A-F) A tables B table with irregular disc C table with reduced disc D ' rare table' of the dorsal E supporting rod and table F supporting rods. Ossicles of dorsal body wall (G-I) G tables H pseudo-buttons I buttons. Ossicles of tentacles J rods." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.79375.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671976" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">2G</figureCitation>
), irregular rim, spinous or smooth; four central holes and eight to eleven peripheral holes, some tables present a second series of smaller peripheral holes. Spire low to medium sized consisting of four pillars, spiny crown with one central hole; single cross-beam. Some tables with button-shape and four big holes. Sometimes up to three peripheral holes are present, spire of four pillars, spiny crown. Irregular buttons (35-70 
<normalizedToken id="FD9C7FA4DF7CA943D86C88B29EDA6A54" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
long) (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="F9061302F0AFD067D998BA5FFF79B436" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Holothuria (Lessonothuria) coronata sp. nov. Holotype, ICML-UNAM 18432. Ossicles of dorsal papillae (A-F) A tables B table with irregular disc C table with reduced disc D ' rare table' of the dorsal E supporting rod and table F supporting rods. Ossicles of dorsal body wall (G-I) G tables H pseudo-buttons I buttons. Ossicles of tentacles J rods." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.79375.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671976" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">2H</figureCitation>
) with smooth edge, three to four pairs of holes. Pseudo-buttons (25-40 
<normalizedToken id="2F6AE1E9DB782F7285BD6DFD2A1DB98E" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
long) (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="EA1F5F33D5A8DB6EED90277E4C798B27" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Holothuria (Lessonothuria) coronata sp. nov. Holotype, ICML-UNAM 18432. Ossicles of dorsal papillae (A-F) A tables B table with irregular disc C table with reduced disc D ' rare table' of the dorsal E supporting rod and table F supporting rods. Ossicles of dorsal body wall (G-I) G tables H pseudo-buttons I buttons. Ossicles of tentacles J rods." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.79375.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671976" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">2I</figureCitation>
) with smooth and irregular edge, two to five holes. Ventral tube feet with three types of tables, plates, supporting rods, and terminal plate. The first type of table with circular disc (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="413FD8A054A1F9E2C24A66BA5C045BB8" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Holothuria (Lessonothuria) coronata sp. nov. Holotype, ICML-UNAM 18432. Ossicles of ventral tube feet (A-F) A tables B tables with reduced disc C table with reduced spire D ' rare table' E supporting rods F plates. Ossicles of ventral body wall (G-I) G tables H buttons I pseudo-buttons." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.79375.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671977" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">3A</figureCitation>
), sometimes irregular (35-55 
<normalizedToken id="66D74B32EC50F1C900FEE7E10026525E" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
wide), and its rim is also irregular, whether spinose or smooth; four central holes and six to twelve peripheral holes. Spire low to medium with four pillars, spiny crown with central hole; single cross-beam. The second type of table bearing a reduced disc (30-40 
<normalizedToken id="7B234CCADB097A6AFA9895163C569B6E" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
wide) (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="8516BF1BCD1DCFDFC3C8053D38CD31E9" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Holothuria (Lessonothuria) coronata sp. nov. Holotype, ICML-UNAM 18432. Ossicles of ventral tube feet (A-F) A tables B tables with reduced disc C table with reduced spire D ' rare table' E supporting rods F plates. Ossicles of ventral body wall (G-I) G tables H buttons I pseudo-buttons." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.79375.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671977" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">3B</figureCitation>
), four central holes and usually lacking peripheral holes, but rarely up to three peripheral holes are present. Medium size spire consisting of four pillars, spiny crown with central hole; single cross-beam. Tables rarely with a reduced spire (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="9E96B03EDB7F44C16512B8E54FCEC36E" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Holothuria (Lessonothuria) coronata sp. nov. Holotype, ICML-UNAM 18432. Ossicles of ventral tube feet (A-F) A tables B tables with reduced disc C table with reduced spire D ' rare table' E supporting rods F plates. Ossicles of ventral body wall (G-I) G tables H buttons I pseudo-buttons." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.79375.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671977" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">3C</figureCitation>
). The third type are button-shaped tables (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="690BBF5DB3CA46593C09799B5EA2BB8D" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Holothuria (Lessonothuria) coronata sp. nov. Holotype, ICML-UNAM 18432. Ossicles of ventral tube feet (A-F) A tables B tables with reduced disc C table with reduced spire D ' rare table' E supporting rods F plates. Ossicles of ventral body wall (G-I) G tables H buttons I pseudo-buttons." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.79375.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671977" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">3D</figureCitation>
) with spire of four pillars, spiny crown, disc with smooth rim and four big central holes. Perforated plates (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="7E4328339B163F45838465AA0BFF386C" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Holothuria (Lessonothuria) coronata sp. nov. Holotype, ICML-UNAM 18432. Ossicles of ventral tube feet (A-F) A tables B tables with reduced disc C table with reduced spire D ' rare table' E supporting rods F plates. Ossicles of ventral body wall (G-I) G tables H buttons I pseudo-buttons." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.79375.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671977" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">3E</figureCitation>
) with spiny irregular edge, 80-135 
<normalizedToken id="D99D97E3DFB1C801C56F2F4599A0AA3E" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
long. Curved supporting rods (130-230 
<normalizedToken id="47553E804BEC414A330B61CB9E2E5EE5" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
) (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="5DC49C1F4BB5B4D5D0D35490A1518AD2" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Holothuria (Lessonothuria) coronata sp. nov. Holotype, ICML-UNAM 18432. Ossicles of ventral tube feet (A-F) A tables B tables with reduced disc C table with reduced spire D ' rare table' E supporting rods F plates. Ossicles of ventral body wall (G-I) G tables H buttons I pseudo-buttons." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.79375.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671977" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">3F</figureCitation>
), the extremes and the central part are widened and perforated, irregular edge, sometimes with few spines. The terminal plates are bigger than the terminal plates from dorsal papillae. Ventral body wall with tables, buttons, and pseudo-buttons. Tables with circular disc (40-50 
<normalizedToken id="0B25E68F629254043CF4791DCB2E9CC1" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
wide) (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="2C578B16F7ECE4208C0630FB889BA0B0" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Holothuria (Lessonothuria) coronata sp. nov. Holotype, ICML-UNAM 18432. Ossicles of ventral tube feet (A-F) A tables B tables with reduced disc C table with reduced spire D ' rare table' E supporting rods F plates. Ossicles of ventral body wall (G-I) G tables H buttons I pseudo-buttons." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.79375.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671977" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">3G</figureCitation>
) perforated by four central holes and eight to twelve peripheral holes. Spire low to medium with four pillars and spiny crown with central hole; single cross-beam. Button-shaped tables present, but scarcely. Disc with four big central holes and smooth rim, spire of four pillars, spiny crown. Buttons (40-50 
<normalizedToken id="1E559D61D9912C037B9C2082CCF0ED4B" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
length) (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="EF5912974FBCC14184ABCFFCA61D81FA" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Holothuria (Lessonothuria) coronata sp. nov. Holotype, ICML-UNAM 18432. Ossicles of ventral tube feet (A-F) A tables B tables with reduced disc C table with reduced spire D ' rare table' E supporting rods F plates. Ossicles of ventral body wall (G-I) G tables H buttons I pseudo-buttons." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.79375.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671977" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">3H</figureCitation>
) are irregular with three pairs of holes and smooth edge. Pseudo-buttons (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="55B26E3B662B6ED8CECF00996164EE8B" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Holothuria (Lessonothuria) coronata sp. nov. Holotype, ICML-UNAM 18432. Ossicles of ventral tube feet (A-F) A tables B tables with reduced disc C table with reduced spire D ' rare table' E supporting rods F plates. Ossicles of ventral body wall (G-I) G tables H buttons I pseudo-buttons." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.79375.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671977" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">3I</figureCitation>
) with smooth edge and two to five holes (35-50 
<normalizedToken id="C85AE2CD53471A4B5580A1273BCD799F" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
). Tentacles with slightly curved rods (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="D653DECD92FB1F3FEE70FC4035BE7B35" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Holothuria (Lessonothuria) coronata sp. nov. Holotype, ICML-UNAM 18432. Ossicles of dorsal papillae (A-F) A tables B table with irregular disc C table with reduced disc D ' rare table' of the dorsal E supporting rod and table F supporting rods. Ossicles of dorsal body wall (G-I) G tables H pseudo-buttons I buttons. Ossicles of tentacles J rods." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.79375.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671976" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">2J</figureCitation>
), both ends are spiny, without perforations (300-600 
<normalizedToken id="586F5499B4FB975BC35DBABA5A7D8E85" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
); some small rods are triradiated. Ossicles are not present in the longitudinal muscles, respiratory trees nor cloaca.
</paragraph>
